Author: DoubleGate <parobek@gmail.com>
Date:   Mon Jun 1 23:36:30 2026 -0400

    feat(v2.0): $2004 OAM-data-bus model — $2004 Stress Fail->PASS (beats Mesen)
    
    Tier 1.2. While the screen is being drawn, $2004 (OAMDATA) returns the value
    the PPU's sprite unit drives on the OAM data bus (the sprite-eval / fetch
    latch), not OAM[OAMADDR]. New feature ppu-oam-data-bus (nes-ppu -> nes-core ->
    nes-test-harness), PROMOTED to default-on.
    
    Implemented as an ISOLATED parallel port of Mesen2 NesPpu::ProcessSpriteEvaluation
    + _oamCopybuffer (own secondary buffer, primary OAM read-only) driving ONLY the
    $2004 read value; the rendering / sprite-zero / overflow / MMC3-fetch FSM is
    untouched, so the change is observable only on a $2004 read during rendering
    (rare in commercial games -> 60-ROM oracle byte-identical).
    
    The section-6 even-cycle $03 is early-PPU (pre-rev-G) behavior NO Mesen config
    reproduces (verified byte-for-byte against a new Mesen $2004 oracle hook; Mesen
    fails this test, with EnablePpuSpriteEvalBug on too). Pinned from the answer key
    (the spec): the eval writes each out-of-range sprite's Y to the frozen
    secondary[8] (last = sprite 63, Y=$03); post-copy-done even cycles read it back.
    Mesen gates that read-back on secondary_addr>=0x20 (rev-G); on early 2C02s it is
    unconditional. One-line fix flips both answer keys.
    
    AccuracyCoin (RAM, branch): 26 -> 25 fail / 81.29% -> 82.01% ($2004 Stress
    Fail->PASS). RustyNES now BEATS Mesen on this test. $2007 Stress (separate
    PPUDATA-during-rendering test) still error 2; Mesen fails it too.
    
    Gates: 60-ROM commercial oracle 60/60 byte-identical, ppu_vbl_nmi 10/10,
    cpu_interrupts_v2 5/5, nes-ppu 41/41, clippy/fmt clean default+feature, no_std
    thumbv7em clean both ways.
    
    See docs/audit/v2.0-2004-stress-oam-data-bus-2026-06-01.md.
    
    Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>

